---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { getRenderableCases } from '../lib/case-utils';

const all = await getRenderableCases();
const fbiCount = all.filter((c) => (c.collection as string) === 'fbiCases').length;
const pursueCount = all.filter((c) => (c.collection as string) === 'pursueCases').length;
---
<Base
  title="Methodology"
  description="What this archive is, what it is not, and how it was assembled."
  serial="METHODOLOGY"
  section="ABOUT"
>
  <header class="ab-hero">
    <div class="ab-hero__breadcrumb">
      <a href="/">Case board</a> <span aria-hidden="true">/</span> <span>Methodology</span>
    </div>
    <p class="ab-hero__eyebrow">What this is, and what it is not</p>
    <h1 class="ab-hero__title">A reading guide to the file, not a campaign for a conclusion.</h1>
  </header>

  <article class="prose ab-body">
    <h2>What this archive is</h2>
    <p>
      On May 8, 2026, the US Department of War published 162 records under the Presidential Unsealing
      and Reporting System for UAP Encounters, called PURSUE. Inside that release was a full,
      OCR-ready copy of the FBI's flying-discs case file, 62-HQ-83894, covering 1944 through 1973.
      This site mirrors the public files and adds a reading layer on top: per-case writeups,
      thread groupings, entity cross-references, a timeline, and a relationship graph.
    </p>
    <p>
      Every case page in this archive cites the page it came from. Source PDFs at war.gov are one
      click away from any dossier. The voice and analysis are mine. The files are the government's.
    </p>

    <h2>What this archive is not</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>Not a "they're hiding aliens" repo.</strong> AARO openly identifies mundane causes
      inside the unresolved tranche, including Russian SU-27/35 fighters and platform parallax.
      The cases that survive AARO's filter survive because the data is insufficient to resolve
      them, not because anyone is hiding alien explanations.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Not a debunk site, either.</strong> Several cases in the release have multi-witness
      evidentiary structure that would warrant follow-up in any other domain. The Bronze Ellipsoid,
      the USPER orb-helicopter chase, the western-US orbs-launching-orbs cluster, and the Apollo 17
      VM6 photo are not closed cases by any honest reading.
    </p>
    <p>
      The honest read: this is the most evidentially structured public-domain UAP material in
      decades, with several genuinely strange cases buried under viral coverage that mostly missed
      them.
    </p>

    <h2>How the archive was built</h2>
    <p>
      The PURSUE Release 01 inventory mirrors AARO's metadata exactly. Where AARO and the news
      cycle disagreed about which cases mattered, this archive sides with the metadata.
    </p>
    <p>
      The FBI 62-HQ-83894 file was mined systematically across 41 archival passes between May 8
      and May 10, 2026, using a CIC investigative-priority filter, a high-signal grep, and a
      cluster-adjacency methodology. That approach favors credentialed witnesses, multi-agency
      coordination patterns, geographically clustered cases at atomic installations and vital
      infrastructure, and institutional-disposition documents like policy memos and baseline
      correspondence patterns. It is not exhaustive. Sections 3, 4, 5, 6, and 9 of the FBI file
      are still being mined.
    </p>

    <h2>How to read this site</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>Start at the <a href="/">case board</a>. The "If you only read these" section surfaces
        16 high-signal cases (4 from PURSUE, 12 from the FBI file).</li>
      <li>Open a dossier. Every page includes provenance to the war.gov source, related cases by
        shared entities, and a list of every entity the case names.</li>
      <li>For broader context, the <a href="/timeline">timeline</a> plots every dated case from
        1944 to 2026, and the <a href="/graph">entity graph</a> shows which people, agencies, and
        places appear together across the file.</li>
      <li>Use Cmd or Ctrl + K to search across all 62 case bodies.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Sourcing</h2>
    <p>
      All government records, including FBI files, AARO documents, State Department cables, and
      war.gov-hosted PDFs, are in the public domain in the United States. The case writeups,
      syntheses, and master reports are released under <a href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/" rel="noopener external">CC BY 4.0</a>.
      Quote freely. A link back is appreciated.
    </p>
    <p>
      The source archive is published at
      <a href="https://github.com/wretcher207/the-ufo-files" rel="noopener external">github.com/wretcher207/the-ufo-files</a>.
      Original PDFs and videos live at <a href="https://www.war.gov/UFO/" rel="noopener external">war.gov/UFO</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Stats</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>{fbiCount} cases from FBI 62-HQ-83894 (Sections 2, 10 mined; 3, 4, 5, 6, 9 pending)</li>
      <li>{pursueCount} cases from PURSUE Release 01 (the four cases that mattered, plus two State Department cables)</li>
      <li>1,262 pages of OCR'd FBI source content backing every claim</li>
      <li>Site published by Dead Pixel Design, May 2026</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What's missing</h2>
    <p>
      No site map for the locations yet. We added geographic coordinates to a small set of headline
      cases; the rest will follow as the next mining passes complete. No video embeds for the 28
      PURSUE videos yet; they hot-link out to war.gov. No live deployment to a standalone domain
      yet; that is the next step.
    </p>

    <h2>Corrections</h2>
    <p>
      If you find an error, open an issue on the source repo. If you have a case the archive has not
      covered yet, open a PR. Quote freely. Cite back to the page.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>

<style>
  .ab-hero { padding: var(--sp-5) 0 var(--sp-6); border-top: 1px solid var(--border); border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); margin-bottom: var(--sp-7); }
  .ab-hero__breadcrumb { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--fs-xs); letter-spacing: var(--tracking-wide); color: var(--fg-3); display: flex; gap: var(--sp-2); margin-bottom: var(--sp-4); }
  .ab-hero__breadcrumb a { color: var(--fg-2); }
  .ab-hero__eyebrow { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--fs-xs); letter-spacing: var(--tracking-wider); text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--fg-3); margin: 0 0 var(--sp-3); }
  .ab-hero__title { font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: var(--fs-3xl); line-height: var(--lh-tight); letter-spacing: var(--tracking-tight); color: var(--fg-1); margin: 0; font-weight: 500; max-width: 26ch; }
  @media (max-width: 640px) { .ab-hero__title { font-size: var(--fs-2xl); } }
  .ab-body { max-width: 70ch; }
</style>
